dataElements.description: Infant/Child 6-59 months of age screened for acute malnutrition (using WHZ/WLZ or MUAC) and/or presence of nutritional oedema. Screening for acute malnutrition. Children (6-59 months) can be screened during outpatient and inpatient care. Screening may occur at first presentation or at any time during their follow-up care which could be as an inpatient or as an outpatient. MAM is defined as weight-for-height -or weight-for-length z-score (WHZ or WLZ) between -3 SD and -2 SD, or MUAC between 115mm and 125mm; SAM is defined as weight-for-height or weight-for-length z-score (WHZ or WLZ) <-3 SD, or MUAC less than 115mm, or presence of nutritional oedema.
dataElements.name: NUT - Child screened for acute malnutrition (wasting and/or nutritional oedema)

dataElements.description: Antenatal contact counselling on iron folic acid (IFA) or iron-containing supplements, inclusive of multiple micronutrient supplements (MMS) by CHW. Counselling to ensure the recommended 30-60 mg of elemental iron and 400 μg (0.4 mg) folic acid  is consumed on a daily basis. In settings where anemia in pregnant women is a severe public health problem (i.e. where at least 40% of pregnant women have a blood hemoglobin [Hb] level < 110 g/L), a daily dose of 60 mg of elemental iron is preferred over a lower dose pf 30 mg. Prevention of maternal anaemia prevents poor birth outcomes,  like low birthweight and preterm births. This includes counselling on potential and temporary side effects which may include nausea, abdominal pain, diarrhoea, constipation and dark stools. These tablets should not be taken on an empty stomach.
dataElements.name: NUT - Antenatal contact with counselling on IFA/iron containing supplement/MMS by CHW

dataElements.description: Antenatal contact counselling on weight gain. Most normal gestational weight gain occurs after 20 weeks of gestation and the definition of “normal” is subject to regional variations, but should take into consideration pre-pregnant body mass index (BMI). According to the Institute of Medicine classification (43), women who are underweight at the start of pregnancy (i.e. BMI < 18.5 kg/m2) should aim to gain 12.5–18 kg, women who are normal weight at the start of pregnancy (i.e. BMI 18.5–24.9 kg/m2) should aim to gain 11.5–16 kg, overweight women (i.e. BMI 25–29.9 kg/m2) should aim to gain 7–11.5 kg, and obese women(i.e. BMI > 30 kg/m2) should aim to gain 5–9 kg. This is based on the notion, that pre-pregnancy or as close to pre-pregnancy BMI can be obtained, including motivating mothers to attend ANC early done in facility
dataElements.name: NUT - Antenatal contact with counselling on appropriate weight gain
